This article is about an executive order issued by President Barack Obama in 2012 to establish a White House Council on Strong Cities, Strong Communities. The purpose of this council is to provide comprehensive technical assistance to local communities in order to help them compete for federal resources more effectively and efficiently. The council is chaired by the Secretary of Housing and Urban Development and the Assistant to the President for Domestic Policy, and includes members from various government agencies. The council's mission is to coordinate efforts across agencies to support communities in developing and implementing economic strategies for sustained growth. The council also conducts outreach to relevant organizations and convenes an annual meeting to share progress and best practices. The executive director of the council is required to provide annual reports on the council's achievements. The order emphasizes that it should be implemented consistent with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations.